sect2.para:
Ample research suggests a positive correlation between gender, age, and posttraumatic symptoms. A meta-analysis of 77 studies revealed that both the risk ofexperiencing traumatic events as well as endorsing PTSD symptomatology was significantly associated with being female, younger, and lower social class status (Brewin et al., 
            2000
         ). A study by Ditlevsen and Elklit (
            2010
         ) supported these findings in a sample of 6548 Nordic people using the Harvard Trauma Questionnaire-Part IV (HTQ-IV). The study found that 27.5% of women and 13.8% of men endorsed PTSD symptoms (Ditlevsen & Elklit, 
            2010
         ).

There is research that also indicates that PTSD is likely to have different developmental trajectories for men and women (Ditlevsen & Elklit,
            2010
         ; Reynolds et al., 
            2015
         ). Overall, multiple studies suggest that PTSD prevalence is lower in late life among both males and females (Brewin et al., 
            2000
         ; Ditlevsen & Elklit, 
            2010
         ; Reynolds et al., 
            2015
         ). However, men showed a decline in HTQ scores in their 40s and the lowest potential for PTSD risk in their 60s to mid-80s (Ditlevsen & Elklit, 
            2010
         ). In the late 80s to 90s, higher rates of PTSD were evident for men (Reynolds et al., 
            2015
         ). Among women, a decrease in PTSD symptoms occurred a decade later than in men (Ditlevsen & Elklit, 
            2010
         ) and continued to decline steadily into late life (Reynolds et al., 
            2015
         ).

In general, studies indicate that racial and ethnic minorities experience more mental health diagnostic inaccuracies as well as disparities in treatment when compared to their White counterparts (Fortuna et al.,
            2009
         ; Samnaliev et al., 
            2009
         ). However, research suggests that the prevalence of lifetime mental disorders among African American, Latino, and Asian adults is lower than Whiles in the USA (Mc Laughlin et al.,
            2019
         ). One possible explanation is that minorities are more resilient in the face of traumatic exposure (Mclaughlin et al., 
            2019
         ). Data from a structured diagnostic interview administered to 34,653 adults revealed that minorities reported lower exposure to traumatic events in comparison to Whites (Roberts et al., 
            2011
         ). However, the lifetime prevalence of PTSD was found to be highest among African Americans (8.7%) in comparison to Whites and Hispanics (7.4% and 7.0%, respectively) and lowest among Asians (4.0%) (Roberts et al., 
            2011
         ). The relatively high prevalence of lifetime PTSD among African Americans may be explained by factors such as discrimination, racial stigmatization, and racial-based abuse, as well as lower socio-economic conditions (Roberts et al., 
            2011
         ). While African Americans are at greater risk for developing PTSD than Whites or other minorities, they are less likely to seek and receive mental health treatment for their trauma. Only 35.3% of Blacks with PTSD symptoms sought any type of treatment (e. g., physician or psychologist) versus 53.3% of Whites with similar symptomology (Roberts et al.,
            2011
         ). Also, only 42% of Hispanics and 32.7% of Asians sought any form of treatment for the disorder. The comparatively low percentage of minorities using mental health treatment for their PTSD symptoms can be explained by several factors, such as negative mental health stigma, cultural beliefs, poor quality or limited availability of resources, and racism or bias in treatment settings (Conner et al., 
            2010
         ).

A significant negative association between stigma and mental health treatment was also found among American Middle Eastern (i. e., Arab or Israeli) individuals (Clement et al.,
            2015
         ). Additional explanations, other than stigma, for a lower percentage of treatment-seeking and use among minorities can be attributed to socio-economic issues (e. g., health insurance plan with coverage for adequate mental health treatment) and knowledge (e. g., education about the options available).

A meta-analysis of 22 studies examining PTSD and other trauma-related disorders among service members returning from OEF and OIF found significant variability in rates for PTSD (Ramchand et al.,
            2010
         ), ranging from a high of 60% among Army National Guard soldiers serving in Iraq (Stecker et al., 
            2007
         ) to a low of 1.6% among Marines serving in Iraq and Afghanistan (Larson et al., 
            2008
         ). While the prevalence of PTSD varied among the studies, there were additional studies where service members completed Department of Defense (DoD) Post Deployment Health Assessment questionnaires within 2 weeks of returning home from service in Iraq. These studies estimated that PTSD rates were approximately 10% (Hoge et al., 
            2006
         ; Milliken et al., 
            2007
         ). However, Ramchand et al. (
            2008
         ) also reported that reassessment of the same participants 6 months after their return from Iraq showed higher PTSD rates. Possible explanations for this increase could be the underreporting of symptoms or the gradual development of symptoms when reintegrating into society (Ramchand et al., 
            2008
         ).

Cultural awareness should be a standard part of clinical practice. Learning about your client’s race, ethnicity, primary language, sexual orientation, religious beliefs, socioeconomic status, and military service is necessary for case conceptualization and treatment planning. Familiarity with recent research concerning the client’s culture and potential idioms of distress is also recommended. The client’s sex and gender can influence the reporting of symptoms. For example, a study found that men who worked in high-stress jobs, such as firefighters, tend to under-report symptoms of trauma (Skeffington et al.,
            2016
         ).

Similarly, women refugees
            refugees
          of Southeast Asian descent were likely to under-report symptoms of trauma resulting from rape because of stigma and shame (Kroll et al., 
            1989
         ). The DSM-IV was the first to introduce the Outline for Cultural Formulation (OCF) to help clinicians organize and integrate cultural considerations of their clients into case formulation (Lewis-Fernández et al., 
            2014
         ). The OCF was revised into a semi-structured interview format and included in the DSM-5 Cultural Formulation of Diagnosis (APA, 
            2013
         ). The purpose of the CFD is to operationalize the process of cultural considerations as part of the case formulation (Lewis-Fernández et al., 
            2014
         ). More psychometrically sound assessment tools are needed to detect cultural considerations that should be integrated into diagnosis and treatment.
